shire, England, United Kingdom":"Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Kingsbury, Warwickshire, England":"Kingsbury, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Cecilia was born in 1039, in Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with Aelfwine 'Ailwin' Alywyne Horne Of Herefordshire, Sheriff of Warwick. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1039–":"1039–Surnud","1042–1083":"1042–1083","1060–1080":"1060–1080","1068–1130":"1068–1130","1061–Male":"1061–Surnud","1068–Male":"1068–Surnud","1039–Female":"1039–Surnud","1080":"1080","1039":"1039","1068":"1068","1130":"1130","1042":"1042","1061":"1061","1083":"1083","ABT 1060":"umbes 1060","1060":"1060","Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Herefordshire, Eng